reviewText: This covers “Pirates” and “Pirates II – Stagnetti’s Revenge” which are two films that use brothel grindhouse women and learning challenged men, the first movie being wonderfully crammed full of intoxicating women showing off their ample assets as often as you hope they will; the second movie apparently some SOB got the bright idea to cut back on the softcore and hope to make a serious movie instead, even though we still see brothel grindhouse women (this time fully clothed) and learning challenged men on the screen.  Had the producer left in the T & A for both movies these would have been home run favorites.  I despise teaser R-rated films that make you watch all the way through and leave you as disappointed as finding out you just lost your job, had your car repossessed, and your wife tells you she’s having her mother move in with you.  The first DVD is definitely 2 thumbs up; the second DVD forgot the pleasure delivering of the first one.  Had the second one’s serious attempt at making a Sci-Fi Fantasy film happened with both films that would be fine.  But the first film was a softcore grindhouse skinfest with voluptuous lovely women getting naked, then the second one can’t even be considered a sequel.  Just buy the first one if you like naked women, and just buy the second one if you prefer a Sci-Fi Fantasy film. The second one is PG by comparison to the almost NC-17 first film  Seriously.
summary: made me salivate for the sequel

reviewText: There's exceptional material here: wood, lead, brass, and silicon. I mean, wooden acting, leaden dialog, brazen synthesexual encounters, and siliceous implants for `most all the ladies. The many anachronisms are just goofy, down to the BoDerek braids, lip-glossed troutpout, and "potassium nitrate" for the gunpowder, rather than nitre or saltpeter.But this isn't a historical drama. It's scarcely even a costume drama, when you think about how often the costumes come off. It's goofy, gaudy, and vulgar. If you want softcore comedy so soft that it's flaccid, you came to the right place.Abandon all hope of decency, logic, artistic value, and common sense, ye who enter herein. (But then, they're pretty over-rated, aren't they?)//wiredweirdPS: There's a collection of bloopers among the extras on this disk. It says a lot about how over-the-top bad this movie is, when you can barely tell the difference between the bloopers and the real acting (or so they call it).
